WEBVTT

00:27.853 --> 00:29.942
♪ ♪

00:51.181 --> 00:53.227
♪ ♪

01:07.676 --> 01:10.592
♪ ♪

01:34.006 --> 01:37.227
♪ Went to sleep last night ♪

01:37.401 --> 01:41.623
♪ I had a kind of dream
for sure ♪

01:43.668 --> 01:47.107
♪ When I woke up
in the morning ♪

01:47.281 --> 01:51.589
♪ Felt like I was
coming down to joy ♪

01:52.808 --> 01:56.377
♪ What did I see,
what did I hear ♪

01:57.726 --> 02:00.685
♪ When I was coming down? ♪

02:03.340 --> 02:06.300
♪ Had a brand-new story ♪

02:06.474 --> 02:10.652
♪ When I was
coming down to joy ♪

02:12.088 --> 02:13.916
♪ Felt so good ♪

02:14.090 --> 02:15.439
♪ Gratitude ♪

02:17.267 --> 02:19.443
♪ When I was coming down ♪

02:21.576 --> 02:23.317
♪ Something quite ♪

02:23.491 --> 02:25.710
♪ Quite profound ♪

02:25.884 --> 02:29.279
♪ That I cried out loud ♪

02:30.541 --> 02:33.109
♪ I got a brand-new story ♪

02:33.283 --> 02:35.242
♪ Brand-new story♪

02:35.416 --> 02:38.375
♪ I was coming down to joy ♪

02:40.464 --> 02:42.336
♪ She was standing there
before me ♪

02:42.510 --> 02:44.686
-♪ There before me♪
-

02:44.860 --> 02:49.343
♪ When I was coming down,
down, down, down ♪

03:07.535 --> 03:09.058
♪ Felt so good... ♪

03:09.232 --> 03:10.799
-FRANKIE: Hello, there.
-How are you, Frankie?

03:12.714 --> 03:14.542
: Buddy!
-MAN: You all right, Paddy?

03:14.716 --> 03:17.153
-Buddy!
-GIRL: You can't catch me!

03:17.327 --> 03:18.807
BOY: Yeah, I'm gonna
catch you! Just wait.

03:18.981 --> 03:20.896
All right?

03:22.811 --> 03:25.292
-Buddy!
-MA: Buddy!

03:26.684 --> 03:28.817
-Buddy!
-

03:28.991 --> 03:32.473
-I'm speedy. You're not.
-I'm gonna get you.

03:32.647 --> 03:34.301
Hiya, Moira. How are you?

03:34.475 --> 03:36.041
Very good, thank you.
How are you?

03:36.216 --> 03:37.826
-I'm good. -BOY: Ah, and
he's dribbling, he's dribbling.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.045
-Score now!
-MA: Buddy!

03:40.220 --> 03:42.439
-Cheat! -No, no cheating.
I did it fair and square.

03:42.613 --> 03:43.919
I'm telling you.

03:44.093 --> 03:46.095
-BUDDY: You nearly got me.

03:46.269 --> 03:47.618
Yes! I did, too!

03:47.792 --> 03:49.054
Hey, Buddy!

03:49.229 --> 03:50.926
BUDDY:
I win! I slayed the dragon!

03:51.100 --> 03:53.842
MOIRA: Your ma's calling you!
Your tea's ready!

03:54.016 --> 03:56.366
All the rest of you, too!

03:56.540 --> 03:58.803
-Yes!
-I'll get you next time, Buddy.

04:00.283 --> 04:02.154
♪ Coming down to joy. ♪

04:02.329 --> 04:03.808
BOY:
You dirty bastard!

04:06.942 --> 04:09.205
-MRS. FORD: Hiya, Buddy.
-Hello, Mrs. Ford.

04:09.379 --> 04:11.076
Have you been fighting
any dragons?

04:11.251 --> 04:13.383
-Only a couple.
-I've got a couple in my house.

04:13.557 --> 04:15.385
-Is that right, Mr. West?
-Aye.

04:15.559 --> 04:17.257
And can you lend us
a shield, Buddy?

04:17.431 --> 04:19.041
I'll see what I can do.

04:19.215 --> 04:20.608
-Say hello to your daddy
for me, will you? -Will do.

04:20.782 --> 04:22.349
Buddy, your ma's calling you
for your tea.

04:22.523 --> 04:23.828
Thanks, Mrs. Kavanagh.

04:24.002 --> 04:25.177
She says it's tripe and onions.

04:25.352 --> 04:27.789
-She did not.
-In a sandwich.

04:27.963 --> 04:30.182
She did not.
She says you're a terrible man.

04:30.357 --> 04:32.097
-She's right.

04:35.840 --> 04:37.973
MAN:
What's going on down there?

04:58.994 --> 05:01.518
: Please, please,
we've done nothing.

05:01.692 --> 05:04.042
MAN 2:
Get the kids inside!

05:04.913 --> 05:07.655
WOMAN:
Get away from here! Go!

05:07.829 --> 05:09.613
MAN 2:
We don't want any trouble!

05:09.787 --> 05:12.355
:
Come on! Get inside!

05:15.619 --> 05:17.839
-

05:18.013 --> 05:19.841
-

05:23.975 --> 05:25.325
Mum!

05:39.251 --> 05:40.252
Buddy!

05:40.427 --> 05:41.863
Ma!

05:42.037 --> 05:44.169
Buddy!

05:45.257 --> 05:48.260
-

05:55.746 --> 06:00.490
Mum! Mum! Mum!

06:00.664 --> 06:03.493
Keep your head down
and don't move!

06:03.667 --> 06:05.147
Will!

06:05.321 --> 06:07.845
-BUDDY: Mum!
-Will!

06:17.246 --> 06:18.508
MRS. KAVANAGH:
Danny, where are you?!

06:20.641 --> 06:22.033
Say nothing to nobody.

06:22.207 --> 06:23.774
-MAN: Catholics out!
-Easy, lads.

06:26.255 --> 06:28.866
Get them upstairs!

06:29.040 --> 06:29.780
Catholics out!

06:29.954 --> 06:33.480
Get in the house! Mummy!

06:35.307 --> 06:38.180
BUDDY:
Mummy! What's happening?!

06:38.354 --> 06:40.312
Keep him there and stay still.

06:44.273 --> 06:45.317
Mum, what are you doing?

06:45.492 --> 06:47.145
Will, stay where you are.

06:47.319 --> 06:48.364
-

06:48.538 --> 06:50.018
BUDDY:
Mum!

06:50.192 --> 06:51.846
-MICKEY: You've been warned!

06:52.020 --> 06:55.023
Get these fuckers
out of your street!

06:55.197 --> 06:56.807
And if you talk to the police,

06:56.981 --> 06:58.809
we'll be back for you, too!

06:58.983 --> 07:01.159
MAN:
Get the Catholics out!

07:13.607 --> 07:15.870
MAN: Get down!
Get yourselves down!

07:19.613 --> 07:21.310
Stand back!

07:48.032 --> 07:50.078
:
Holy God.

07:53.385 --> 07:55.387
NEWSMAN: Belfast was in shock
this morning as the impact

07:55.562 --> 07:58.303
of last night's rioting
was all too clear.

07:58.478 --> 08:00.305
Small numbers of Catholics
still peacefully living

08:00.480 --> 08:02.612
in Protestant areas
were targeted.

08:02.786 --> 08:04.396
Their houses were attacked
and marked,

08:04.571 --> 08:05.920
and intimidation may force them

08:06.094 --> 08:07.791
to leave their homes
completely.

08:07.965 --> 08:10.011
Can these tightly-knit
neighborhoods ever return

08:10.185 --> 08:13.144
to the peace they shared
together only 24 hours ago?

08:13.318 --> 08:14.885
-Further reports suggest...
-

08:15.059 --> 08:17.322
MAN: Up front, Frank.
I'll show you where I put them.

08:17.497 --> 08:18.976
Look, we need to get
this barricade up

08:19.150 --> 08:20.891
before those kids
come back, okay?

08:21.065 --> 08:22.502
MAN: Are we taking all these
paving stones to the barricade?

08:22.676 --> 08:24.199
-We taking them all down?
-MAN: We need them all.

08:26.810 --> 08:28.072
WOMAN: Is poor Jane okay?
Is she all right?

08:28.246 --> 08:29.465
MAN:
Don't you worry, Paddy.

08:29.639 --> 08:31.075
We're not gonna let them
back here again.

08:31.249 --> 08:32.424
You're as welcome
on this street as any of us.

08:32.599 --> 08:34.296
MAN:
All right, Buddy?

08:34.470 --> 08:35.602
MAN: We're gonna have to go
down the yard and get more.

08:35.776 --> 08:36.864
We've got
four more houses to do,

08:37.038 --> 08:38.692
and that's
the last pane of glass.

08:38.866 --> 08:39.997
WOMAN: Apparently, Fergus
didn't come home last night.

08:40.171 --> 08:41.695
I'm gonna go see
Mrs. McGuinness now.

08:41.869 --> 08:43.261
MAN: It's all right.
I saw Fergus down the road.

08:43.435 --> 08:44.741
-He's coming now.
-MAN: We have to do this.

08:44.915 --> 08:45.829
The police aren't
going to protect us,

08:46.003 --> 08:47.396
so we have to do it ourselves.

08:47.570 --> 08:48.571
MAN: Is that all
you can take in a barrow?

08:48.745 --> 08:50.268
WOMAN:
Kids, please, go inside.

08:50.442 --> 08:51.748
I don't want you out here
until it's all safe again.

08:51.922 --> 08:53.620
-Come on. -MAN: Come on,
load them up here.

08:53.794 --> 08:55.012
WOMAN: Would you look at the
poor children with that load.

08:55.186 --> 08:56.579
MAN: Can you wheel that
up to the front?

08:56.753 --> 08:58.363
Frankie will show you
where we're putting it.

08:58.538 --> 09:00.148
MAN: Tell Paddy I'll be there
in a minute to fix that.

09:00.322 --> 09:01.715
I've just got to nip into
the house and get my tools.

09:01.889 --> 09:02.542
WOMAN: Watch yourself
getting up there, love.

09:04.282 --> 09:04.805
MAN: Put that pallet
over here. Over here.

09:06.415 --> 09:07.634
MAN: Get them kids to stay away
from them sharp edges.

09:07.808 --> 09:10.201
MAN:
Pull them rocks up.

09:10.375 --> 09:12.116
MAN: Everything.
Put that washing machine in.

09:12.290 --> 09:13.683
-

09:13.857 --> 09:16.120
WOMAN: Come on,
let's get this all done.

09:25.565 --> 09:26.914
NEWSMAN: The likeliest move is
to bring troops into Belfast

09:27.088 --> 09:28.959
in the hope of avoiding
further clashes

09:29.133 --> 09:32.093
between rioters and police,
particularly the B-Specials.

09:32.267 --> 09:33.573
-MAN: Stand to the side!
-Another 600 troops will be

09:33.747 --> 09:35.313
available this afternoon.

09:35.487 --> 09:36.750
-MAN: Off these streets now!
-

09:40.492 --> 09:42.712
Get off the road! Stand back!

09:51.895 --> 09:53.157
:
We're not stupid!

09:53.331 --> 09:55.159
You can't keep us
in our houses!

09:55.333 --> 09:57.031
NEWSMAN: The men of the 3rd
Battalion of the Light Infantry

09:57.205 --> 09:59.033
fly in from Plymouth
to plug the gap

09:59.207 --> 10:00.469
left by the use of troops.

10:00.643 --> 10:02.036
A curfew is another possibility

10:02.210 --> 10:04.081
which is being
widely mentioned.

10:04.255 --> 10:05.561
I've just come from
the airport now.

10:05.735 --> 10:07.128
I've literally just come
from the airport.

10:07.302 --> 10:08.303
I live in that street.
That's my kids there.

10:08.477 --> 10:09.870
I live in number 96.

10:10.044 --> 10:12.002
MRS. FORD:
Get up there quick. Quick.

10:12.176 --> 10:13.438
MA:
Christ.

10:17.617 --> 10:19.444
-SOLDIER: Stop!
-MAN: Just let him through...

10:19.619 --> 10:20.707
SOLDIER: Where do you think
you're going, love?

10:20.881 --> 10:22.012
To bring my husband home.

10:22.186 --> 10:23.231
That's him
on the other side there.

10:23.405 --> 10:24.624
SOLDIER:
Where's he been, then?

10:24.798 --> 10:25.973
MA:
None of your bloody business.

10:26.147 --> 10:27.801
Not with you
in your hour of need?

10:27.975 --> 10:29.063
-That's a bit off, isn't it?
-He works away in England.

10:29.237 --> 10:30.804
Does he?
What kind of work is that?

10:30.978 --> 10:32.501
-He's a joiner.
-I see.

10:32.675 --> 10:34.242
And has he joined
any of these groups

10:34.416 --> 10:35.852
making all this mess
in your street?

10:36.026 --> 10:37.245
He knew nothing about
the whole bloody thing.

10:37.419 --> 10:38.942
That's why he's here now.

10:39.116 --> 10:40.552
He's come home from
his work to see his family.

10:40.727 --> 10:42.554
Glad to hear it, madam.

10:43.643 --> 10:44.992
-MA: Hi.
-Hi.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.780
They nearly had you there,
Steve McQueen.

10:50.954 --> 10:52.390
PA: I'll have you
in a second, Frankie.

10:52.564 --> 10:54.131
-Come on, you two.
-Hi, boys.

10:54.305 --> 10:56.133
-

10:58.483 --> 10:59.615
:
Stay in your homes tonight.

10:59.789 --> 11:00.790
-Thank you very much.
-Okay?

11:00.964 --> 11:02.400
Aye.

11:05.577 --> 11:08.189
CAPTAIN KIRK:
Space, the final frontier.

11:09.233 --> 11:10.974
These are the voyages of

11:11.148 --> 11:12.933
-the Starship Enterprise...
-GRANNY: Did they attack you?

11:13.107 --> 11:15.718
No. It was only
the Catholic houses.

11:15.892 --> 11:18.286
Them boyos want them out.

11:18.460 --> 11:20.375
Them peoples don't give you
any bother in that street,

11:20.549 --> 11:22.072
-do they?
-Not at all.

11:22.246 --> 11:24.771
Sure, they're friends,
they're family, same as us.

11:24.945 --> 11:26.381
They just kick
with the left foot.

11:26.555 --> 11:28.165
Exactly.

11:28.339 --> 11:30.341
Sure, my best friend in
the street is Mrs. Ganjawala.

11:30.515 --> 11:31.865
She's Indian.

11:32.039 --> 11:33.736
She even comes to
the wee mission with me.

11:33.910 --> 11:36.347
Well, them curries,
I tried one once.

11:36.521 --> 11:38.698
I had to wear
a nappy for a week.

11:41.526 --> 11:44.007
-Will.
-WILL: Oh, Mum. Sorry, Granny.

11:44.181 --> 11:46.053
POP: Ah, she's well able
to handle herself.

11:46.227 --> 11:47.881
PA: It's being so cheerful
keeps you going, isn't it?

11:48.055 --> 11:49.621
Sure, I'm not gonna be
running up the Cave Hill

11:52.146 --> 11:53.625
-MA: It's just not knowing.
-GRANNY: That's not easy.

11:53.800 --> 11:55.410
MA: How it's gonna
affect their schooling.

11:55.584 --> 11:57.281
Will, would you
turn that telly off

11:57.455 --> 11:59.327
-and talk to your granny?
-Hi, Pop.

11:59.501 --> 12:01.111
Hiya, Buddy.

12:03.026 --> 12:05.507
PA: Does the doctor
want to see you again?

12:05.681 --> 12:07.901
He's given me a letter
for the hospital.

12:08.075 --> 12:10.120
-PA: And did you go?
-There's no point.

12:13.471 --> 12:16.997
I think you've a few
big decisions to make, son.

12:19.956 --> 12:21.784
Did you clear up
that wee bit of trouble

12:21.958 --> 12:23.699
-we were talking about?
-GRANNY: Hey, wee fellas.

12:24.831 --> 12:26.876
We're not deaf back here.

12:37.104 --> 12:39.323
Oh, yes, we've friends
on the Protestant side.

12:39.497 --> 12:40.934
They weren't friends last night.

12:41.108 --> 12:42.631
They weren't
friends last night, though.

12:42.805 --> 12:45.242
BUDDY: Paddy Kavanagh told me
as long as Catholics

12:45.416 --> 12:48.158
keep confessing everything bad
that they do to a priest,

12:48.332 --> 12:49.812
then they can do
whatever they want

12:49.986 --> 12:51.596
and God will forgive them
all the time.

12:51.771 --> 12:53.381
Well, Paddy Kavanagh's
family's not gonna be living

12:53.555 --> 12:55.035
in this street for much longer,
so you'd better check

12:55.209 --> 12:56.906
he's not taking
the hand out of you.

12:57.080 --> 12:58.865
Ugh, I don't know how it works.

12:59.039 --> 13:00.736
They get a lot of water thrown
on them and then they're okay.

13:00.910 --> 13:02.259
I think that's it.

13:02.433 --> 13:04.044
-Why aren't you going, too?
-

13:04.218 --> 13:05.480
'Cause me and your father
have business to discuss.

13:05.654 --> 13:06.916
God understands.

13:09.223 --> 13:11.007
-What are those?
- My little secret.

13:11.181 --> 13:12.835
Now, come on.

13:14.271 --> 13:16.796
I've had too much God
for one day.

13:16.970 --> 13:19.711
Well, your granny says you can
never have too much God.

13:19.886 --> 13:21.061
You might need him
before too long.

13:21.235 --> 13:22.802
Look, mind your nonsense
for now,

13:22.976 --> 13:24.281
and I'll take youse all
to the pictures tomorrow.

13:24.455 --> 13:26.196
Brilliant!

13:26.370 --> 13:27.719
Robin and the 7 Hoodsis on

13:27.894 --> 13:29.286
in the afternoon
at the Capitol.

13:29.460 --> 13:31.288
-Paddy saw it.
-MA: Wait, is that gangsters?

13:31.462 --> 13:33.856
-WILL: It's a blinking musical.
-No, it's not.

13:34.030 --> 13:36.337
There's Little John
and swords and everything.

13:36.511 --> 13:37.773
MA: Well, you can't go
tomorrow afternoon.

13:37.947 --> 13:39.296
Your cousins will be here.

13:39.470 --> 13:40.689
Your aunties and uncles
want to say goodbye

13:40.863 --> 13:41.995
to your father
before he goes back.

13:42.169 --> 13:43.431
But, Daddy,
are you not gonna be

13:43.605 --> 13:45.128
a vigilante on our barricade?

13:45.302 --> 13:47.391
No more talk
about bloody barricades.

13:47.565 --> 13:49.263
That whole nonsense
will stop soon enough.

13:49.437 --> 13:51.439
MA: I wouldn't be
too sure about that.

13:52.657 --> 13:54.964
PA: Hey, less of
the long face, son.

13:55.138 --> 13:57.053
These two can go
and pray for it to stop now,

13:57.227 --> 13:59.186
and we'll all go to the big
picture house in town tomorrow,

13:59.360 --> 14:01.188
Daddy will pick the film,
and we'll forget about

14:01.362 --> 14:02.624
this whole bunch of eejits

14:02.798 --> 14:04.147
before I have to go
back to work.

14:04.321 --> 14:05.845
Was that our side
that done all that

14:06.019 --> 14:09.109
to them Catholic houses
in our street, Daddy?

14:09.283 --> 14:12.286
There is no our side
and their side in our street.

14:12.460 --> 14:15.071
Or there didn't
used to be, anyway.

14:15.245 --> 14:17.378
It's all bloody religion.
That's the problem.

14:17.552 --> 14:19.467
Then why are you
sending us to church?

14:19.641 --> 14:21.338
Because your granny'd
kill me if I didn't.

14:21.512 --> 14:24.080
But, Daddy,
if we were Catholics,

14:24.254 --> 14:25.865
we could not go to church,

14:26.039 --> 14:27.388
and then every once
in a wee while,

14:27.562 --> 14:29.259
we could go in and confess,

14:29.433 --> 14:31.261
and then they'd have to tell us
we were forgiven

14:31.435 --> 14:33.611
and we wouldn't have to go
in again for ages.

14:35.265 --> 14:37.267
PA:
I've nothing against Catholics.

14:37.441 --> 14:39.443
But it's a religion of fear.

14:40.705 --> 14:43.534
Protestants, you will die!

14:44.579 --> 14:45.754
Agonizingly!

14:45.928 --> 14:49.236
And where will you go

14:49.410 --> 14:51.978
when you shuffle off
this pestilential mortal coil?

14:52.152 --> 14:53.631
Where?!

14:55.982 --> 14:57.940
Well, I will tell you where.

14:58.941 --> 15:00.334
Picture the scene.

15:00.508 --> 15:03.467
A fork in the road.

15:03.641 --> 15:09.082
In one direction,
a straight and narrow highway.

15:09.256 --> 15:13.825
In the other,
a long and winding road

15:14.000 --> 15:19.092
which stretches down and away
into an unknowable distance.

15:19.266 --> 15:23.661
One will take you to the bosom
of the Lord's grace,

15:23.835 --> 15:27.927
forever and a day
caress you with beatific love.

15:28.101 --> 15:33.802
And the other will spew you
into an eternal pit

15:33.976 --> 15:36.979
of sulfurous suffering,
pustulating pain,

15:37.153 --> 15:39.199
from which you will never, ever,

15:39.373 --> 15:41.897
through the seven circles
of hell escape!

15:42.071 --> 15:44.639
And I ask you here and now...

15:46.380 --> 15:49.209
...which road will you take?!

15:51.124 --> 15:53.126
Now, money.

15:54.214 --> 15:55.171
BUDDY and WILL:
Thanks very much.

15:55.345 --> 15:56.825
Really good.

16:02.048 --> 16:04.093
♪ ♪

16:33.122 --> 16:35.168
♪ ♪

16:46.657 --> 16:49.182
MA: Remember, one slice
per sandwich.

16:49.356 --> 16:50.879
I don't want to be
giving too much away.

16:51.053 --> 16:52.750
:
With regard to the explosive--

16:52.924 --> 16:55.840
I think that's a fair word--
situation in Northern Ireland,

16:56.015 --> 16:58.234
are we getting near
to the point where you,

16:58.408 --> 17:00.019
as prime minister of
the United Kingdom government,

17:00.193 --> 17:01.933
will feel it necessary
to intervene

17:02.108 --> 17:04.936
and use the supreme authority
which is yours in law

17:05.111 --> 17:07.417
either to remedy grievances
or to ensure order?

17:07.591 --> 17:09.376
Is it almost ready?

17:09.550 --> 17:11.247
:
If that became necessary,

17:11.421 --> 17:15.121
of course, I shouldn't shrink
from doing whatever was needed.

17:15.295 --> 17:17.819
Uh, we have been deeply
concerned about the problem

17:17.993 --> 17:20.039
of civil rights
in Northern Ireland.

17:20.213 --> 17:21.953
I've paid tribute...

17:22.128 --> 17:23.520
GUARD:
Make an orderly queue

17:23.694 --> 17:25.044
to be allowed entrance
to the street, please.

17:27.698 --> 17:29.918
FRANKIE: All right,
what have we got left now?

17:30.092 --> 17:31.659
Not doing a strip search
this time, eh, Frankie?

17:31.833 --> 17:33.269
FRANKIE:
Whose do you belong to?

17:33.443 --> 17:34.836
You know full bloody well
who we belong to.

17:35.010 --> 17:36.359
I'm taking my wife
down to her sister's,

17:36.533 --> 17:37.621
like I've been doing
all my bloody life.

17:37.795 --> 17:39.058
-House number?
-There's no number.

17:39.232 --> 17:40.842
Just a name.

17:41.016 --> 17:42.757
-What's the name?
-Arsehole.

17:44.498 --> 17:45.194
Very funny, Mack.
Always the joker, eh?

17:45.368 --> 17:46.891
On you go.

17:47.066 --> 17:48.502
We won't worry about
their name and number now.

17:48.676 --> 17:50.591
We know where they live.

17:52.375 --> 17:54.160
-Whoo. You like that?
-

18:01.602 --> 18:03.169
How's that, then,
Ginger Rogers, huh?

18:10.263 --> 18:12.221
MA: Whoo. Come on you,
Fred Astaire.

18:12.395 --> 18:14.484
♪ ♪

18:28.455 --> 18:31.022
-You can tell them
by their names. -How?

18:31.197 --> 18:34.461
Well, if he's a Patrick
or a Sean, he's a Catholic,

18:34.635 --> 18:36.550
and if he's a Billy or a
William, he's a protestant.

18:36.724 --> 18:38.247
There's more names
than that, though.

18:38.421 --> 18:39.727
I know that.

18:39.901 --> 18:41.598
I'm just saying,
them's the obvious ones.

18:42.773 --> 18:44.732
What about Morris?

18:44.906 --> 18:46.951
Uh, don't know.

18:47.126 --> 18:49.606
We've a wee fella down
our street called Thomas.

18:49.780 --> 18:51.956
-What's he?
-Protestant definitely.

18:52.131 --> 18:54.350
He's not. He's a Catholic.

18:54.524 --> 18:56.047
-No, he's not.
-He is.

18:56.222 --> 18:58.049
Sure, they burnt his house out
the other night

18:58.224 --> 19:00.791
'cause his family is Catholic.

19:00.965 --> 19:02.750
Sure, we've a cousin
called Thomas.

19:02.924 --> 19:04.839
I know. That's what I'm saying.

19:05.013 --> 19:07.363
Well, how the hell are you
supposed to know, then?

19:07.537 --> 19:09.148
You have to get taught it.

19:09.322 --> 19:10.671
Who teaches you?

19:10.845 --> 19:12.151
So the doctor says,
"Listen, John,

19:12.325 --> 19:13.804
I've got some bad news
and worse."

19:13.978 --> 19:15.806
And John says, "Oh, no.
Wh-What's the bad news?"

19:15.980 --> 19:18.983
And he goes, "Well, you've only
got 24 hours to live."

19:19.158 --> 19:20.594
John says,
"That's-that's awful.

19:20.768 --> 19:21.943
What could be worse than that?"

19:22.117 --> 19:23.684
Doctor says,
"Well, I've been trying

19:23.858 --> 19:25.990
-to get ahold of you
since yesterday." -

19:26.165 --> 19:29.168
-Why do you even have to know?
-In case they attack you.

19:29.342 --> 19:30.908
-When?
-When you're out and about.

19:31.082 --> 19:32.475
Well, if they're attacking you,

19:32.649 --> 19:33.781
they're not gonna stop
and tell you their name.

19:33.955 --> 19:35.652
It wouldn't get to that stage.

19:35.826 --> 19:38.829
-Why? -'Cause you use your
secret knowledge to bluff them.

19:39.003 --> 19:40.701
What are you talking about?

19:40.875 --> 19:42.529
They can just come up to you
when you're not expecting it

19:42.703 --> 19:45.749
and ask you, "Are you
Protestant or Catholic?"

19:45.923 --> 19:47.403
But it's a trick question,
you see,

19:47.577 --> 19:49.057
'cause they don't
tell you what they are.

19:49.231 --> 19:52.103
And what do you say then
to not get a dig in the gob?

19:52.278 --> 19:53.844
-"I'm a Catholic"?
-Wrong.

19:54.018 --> 19:55.716
That's exactly
what they think you will say.

19:55.890 --> 19:57.326
They think you're trying
to bluff them.

19:57.500 --> 19:59.154
But you have to
double-bluff them.

19:59.328 --> 20:02.070
-How?
-You say, "I'm a Protestant."

20:02.244 --> 20:04.986
-But I am a Protestant.
-That's the point!

20:05.160 --> 20:06.901
BUDDY: Blanchflower's now
at the halfway line.

20:07.075 --> 20:08.642
-He looks up.
-

20:08.816 --> 20:12.559
Is there nothing this
Spurs right-half cannot do?

20:12.733 --> 20:15.257
Perfect through ball!

20:18.042 --> 20:19.827
Nice pass, son.

20:20.001 --> 20:22.264
Would you go on away in and
tell your pa I'd like to have

20:22.438 --> 20:24.484
a wee chat with him, please?

20:25.876 --> 20:27.704
Tell him it's Billy Clanton.

20:27.878 --> 20:28.879
And McLaury.

20:31.752 --> 20:33.362
PA:
What do you want?

20:33.536 --> 20:35.103
BILLY: We're looking to cleanse
the community a wee bit.

20:35.277 --> 20:38.541
You wouldn't want to be
the odd man out in this street.

20:38.715 --> 20:41.457
You saw what happened to your
neighbors from the other side.

20:41.631 --> 20:43.677
You touch my family
and I'll kill you.

20:43.851 --> 20:44.982
Calm down, fella.

20:45.156 --> 20:46.897
I'm a Protestant, like yourself.

20:47.071 --> 20:49.160
-MACK: All all right?
-Aye, it's okay, Mackie.

20:49.335 --> 20:51.162
BILLY:
Look, things get out of hand

20:51.337 --> 20:53.295
pretty quick round these parts.

20:54.601 --> 20:56.646
Cash or commitment.

20:58.692 --> 21:00.084
The boys who cleaned up
your street

21:00.259 --> 21:01.999
have made me their new
local chief.

21:02.173 --> 21:05.133
So, you can report to me
with either.

21:05.307 --> 21:06.569
All right?

21:06.743 --> 21:08.571
Have a wee think.

21:08.745 --> 21:10.051
I'll be in touch.

21:16.231 --> 21:17.537
Buddy, come on.

21:17.711 --> 21:18.886
Come and show me
how to play this game.

21:19.060 --> 21:21.018
Come on.
Let's have a look. Huh?

21:21.192 --> 21:23.456
♪ ♪

21:35.685 --> 21:36.730
See you, now.

21:40.168 --> 21:41.604
All the big boys have left.

21:41.778 --> 21:42.910
Buddy, give your brother
a hand there, will you?

21:43.084 --> 21:44.303
Pick this sofa up, right?

21:44.477 --> 21:46.000
MA:
Here, can you give us a hand?

21:46.174 --> 21:48.132
SOLDIER:
Yes, ma'am.

21:48.307 --> 21:49.569
MA:
You want to set your gun down?

21:49.743 --> 21:51.397
SOLDIER:
No, it's all right, thank you.

21:52.963 --> 21:54.791
MA: Now, don't you be
scratching my walls with that.

21:54.965 --> 21:56.315
PA:
You got it? Right now, hold on.

21:56.489 --> 21:58.273
This worked earlier.

21:58.447 --> 22:00.275
I'll go in first.

22:01.363 --> 22:03.539
-All right?
-Stewart.

22:03.713 --> 22:05.498
-MR. STEWART: Frankie.
-FRANKIE: All right?

22:05.672 --> 22:07.108
All right, Frankie?

22:07.282 --> 22:08.370
Is that you all this time
at the barricades?

22:08.544 --> 22:09.893
Somebody has to.

22:10.067 --> 22:11.330
Better me than Billy Clanton.

22:11.504 --> 22:13.027
Aye.

22:13.201 --> 22:15.203
Not many people chose this.

22:15.377 --> 22:16.857
There's a few men hiding
behind them barricades.

22:17.031 --> 22:18.380
And they'll keep hiding

22:18.554 --> 22:19.338
where they're afraid
for their families.

22:19.512 --> 22:21.340
It's a waiting game now.

22:21.514 --> 22:22.950
When it's time
for that wall to come down,

22:23.124 --> 22:25.474
I'll be the first
to swing a hammer, but now?

22:25.648 --> 22:28.347
"They also serve
who stand and wait."

22:30.653 --> 22:33.047
We can't all be acting
the Lone Ranger.

22:46.103 --> 22:48.323
: This is
a story of long, long ago,

22:48.497 --> 22:50.978
when the world
was just beginning.

22:51.152 --> 22:52.675
A young world.

22:52.849 --> 22:55.199
A world early
in the morning of time.

23:09.126 --> 23:11.825
No wonder
you brought us to this.

23:11.999 --> 23:14.218
It's educational for the boys.

23:14.393 --> 23:15.698
Aye.

23:18.309 --> 23:20.529
MA: Raquel Welch is
a hell of an education.

23:29.669 --> 23:32.149
PA: If people ask you to join
anything, deliver anything,

23:32.323 --> 23:35.109
do messages for anybody,
you do nothing, okay?

23:35.283 --> 23:37.416
You tell your ma, she'll
tell me, and I'll sort it.

23:37.590 --> 23:39.069
-You understand me?
-WILL: Yes, Daddy.

23:39.243 --> 23:41.550
Very good.
I'm proud of you, son.

23:41.724 --> 23:43.030
Now get off to bed,
the pair of you.

23:43.204 --> 23:44.858
I'm up too early
in the morning to see you,

23:45.032 --> 23:47.208
so make sure you get to school
all right, all right?

23:47.382 --> 23:49.210
Don't mess your mother about,
and I'll see you in two weeks.

23:49.384 --> 23:50.907
-Okay?
-Yes, Daddy.

23:51.081 --> 23:52.082
Good boys.

23:53.170 --> 23:56.043
MINISTER:
A fork in the road.

23:56.217 --> 24:01.004
In one direction,
a straight and narrow highway.

24:02.789 --> 24:05.313
Which road will you take?!

24:09.273 --> 24:10.666
MA:
You're running round here

24:10.840 --> 24:12.189
like the man
in the big picture,

24:12.363 --> 24:13.626
not paying your taxes

24:13.800 --> 24:14.844
and spending all our money
on horses.

24:15.018 --> 24:16.411
It's the building trade.

24:16.585 --> 24:18.152
I told you it doesn't work
the normal way.

24:18.326 --> 24:19.545
I told you I had it covered.

24:19.719 --> 24:21.068
I was the one
who had it covered.

24:21.242 --> 24:22.417
No, you had us paying
three years of back tax.

24:22.591 --> 24:24.027
To keep you out of bloody jail.

24:24.201 --> 24:26.334
We're drowning in debt.

24:26.508 --> 24:28.336
PA: We're near done
with the back tax.

24:28.510 --> 24:30.512
Ten pound a month
for three bloody years.

24:30.686 --> 24:32.819
This is the time to think
about making a new start.

24:32.993 --> 24:35.517
I know nothing else
but Belfast.

24:35.691 --> 24:37.040
Exactly.

24:37.214 --> 24:39.260
There's a whole world out there.

24:39.434 --> 24:41.523
We can give these boys a
better chance than we ever had.

24:41.697 --> 24:44.657
There's Commonwealth countries
needing tradesmen.

24:44.831 --> 24:47.050
The government will give you
assisted passage.

24:47.224 --> 24:49.183
We can get the whole family
to the other side of the world

24:49.357 --> 24:51.011
for ten pound.

24:51.185 --> 24:52.926
We're living in a civil war,

24:53.100 --> 24:56.190
and I'm not here
to protect my family.

24:58.975 --> 25:00.934
MA:
What are those supposed to be?

25:01.108 --> 25:03.153
PA:
An escape route.

25:10.160 --> 25:12.467
SOLDIER:
Get this street locked down.

25:12.641 --> 25:14.817
GIRL: Come on, get a move on.
We're gonna be late again.

25:14.991 --> 25:16.427
-Come on!
-

25:16.602 --> 25:17.994
:
Throughout the night,

25:18.168 --> 25:20.127
sniping became
the tactic of the rioters.

25:20.301 --> 25:21.824
As we drove past a side street,

25:21.998 --> 25:24.435
three men on the corner
dived for cover.

25:24.610 --> 25:25.915
-It's not bad, though, is it?
-A young man with a revolver

25:26.089 --> 25:27.613
asked us for a lift.

25:27.787 --> 25:29.745
At 4:00 this morning,
RUC turned us back

25:29.919 --> 25:31.791
-from the Falls area.
-Yeah.

25:31.965 --> 25:33.880
NEWSMAN: Snipers, they said,
were still at work,

25:34.054 --> 25:36.056
and in the distance,
one heard the ominous burst

25:36.230 --> 25:37.623
of machine-gun fire.

25:37.797 --> 25:39.668
The scene terrified me,

25:39.842 --> 25:42.192
but it reminded an
American colleague of Harlem,

25:42.366 --> 25:44.151
but, he added, it seems easier
to get guns here.

25:44.325 --> 25:46.109
MA:
One more left.

25:46.283 --> 25:48.459
NEWSMAN: Dawn over Belfast
today showed a grim scene,

25:48.634 --> 25:50.418
buildings scarred by fire,

25:50.592 --> 25:52.594
thousands of pounds' worth
of damage caused,

25:52.768 --> 25:54.683
and, of course,
the tragic loss of life.

25:54.857 --> 25:57.860
It's been a night of shame for
Belfast, one that will live on

25:58.034 --> 25:59.209
in the memories
of its people...

25:59.383 --> 26:00.776
MA:
Come on, you two. School.

26:06.521 --> 26:08.044
MISS LEWIS:
Walking, please. No running.

26:08.218 --> 26:10.481
-BOY: Morning, miss.

26:10.656 --> 26:13.484
STUDENTS:
Twelve elevens are 132.

26:13.659 --> 26:17.401
Twelve twelves are 144.

26:17.576 --> 26:19.316
MISS LEWIS: Well, I'm pleased
to say your times tables

26:19.490 --> 26:20.840
were a lot more impressive
to hear

26:21.014 --> 26:22.363
than your test scores
were to read.

26:22.537 --> 26:23.625
The whole point
of these weekly tests

26:23.799 --> 26:25.584
is to monitor your progress.

26:25.758 --> 26:29.109
The best will sit directly by
my desk, the seat of learning,

26:29.283 --> 26:31.328
and the rest of you will view
your Sisyphean struggles

26:31.502 --> 26:33.504
from the distance
you have imposed upon yourself

26:33.679 --> 26:34.636
by a lack of application.

26:34.810 --> 26:37.291
Billy Clanton Junior, 17%.

26:37.465 --> 26:39.119
Bottom row, seat 12.

26:39.293 --> 26:41.121
Rachel, seat 11.

26:41.295 --> 26:42.513
Martin to seat ten.

26:42.688 --> 26:43.776
Freddie, seat eight.

26:43.950 --> 26:45.734
Karen to seat four.

26:45.908 --> 26:50.173
And in the medal positions
this week, with 72%, in bronze,

26:50.347 --> 26:52.393
is Buddy, seat three.

26:54.090 --> 26:55.962
And, of course, in silver
again, we have Ron,

26:56.136 --> 26:58.791
and Catherine with
the gold yet again this week.

26:58.965 --> 27:01.228
Congratulations, Catherine.
Very well done.

27:07.147 --> 27:10.672
The wee girl still showing
some interest, yeah?

27:10.846 --> 27:13.588
She looks at me sometimes,
but we're not allowed to talk

27:13.762 --> 27:16.330
in the class,
so I can't say anything.

27:16.504 --> 27:17.984
And then when we go out
to the playground,

27:18.158 --> 27:20.464
she always goes off
with the other girls.

27:21.770 --> 27:23.554
Anyways, I think
she loves that other fella.

27:23.729 --> 27:25.992
Ah, you don't know that
for sure.

27:26.166 --> 27:28.385
Women are very mysterious.

27:28.559 --> 27:30.866
And women can smash
your face in, too, mister.

27:31.040 --> 27:33.913
Your granny's become
less mysterious over the years.

27:34.087 --> 27:35.697
So, you really like her?

27:35.871 --> 27:38.613
When I grow up,
I want to marry her.

27:38.787 --> 27:41.007
Yeah, sounds like
you really like her.

27:41.181 --> 27:43.792
You know,
she's not only at school.

27:43.966 --> 27:46.839
You could see
where she lives maybe.

27:47.013 --> 27:49.058
It's Reynolds Drive,
four houses in from the right,

27:49.232 --> 27:50.451
the one with the wonky eight.

27:50.625 --> 27:52.453
Oh, you've done your research.

27:52.627 --> 27:55.108
I pass it every day
on my way home.

27:55.282 --> 27:58.154
I try to look in,
but she never sees me.

27:58.328 --> 28:00.417
She's always doing
her bloody homework.

28:00.591 --> 28:02.637
If she were a wee bit
more stupid like me,

28:02.811 --> 28:04.595
we'd be sitting together
by now.

28:04.770 --> 28:08.687
Ah, "a pity beyond all telling
is hid in the heart of love."

28:08.861 --> 28:10.689
Oh, he's full of
pretty answers, that one.

28:10.863 --> 28:12.168
Come on, it's time to go.

28:12.342 --> 28:13.604
I don't want your mommy
shouting at me

28:13.779 --> 28:14.823
because you're late.

28:14.997 --> 28:16.999
-Cheerio, son.
-Cheerio.

28:20.481 --> 28:22.875
GRANNY:
Here, take this threepenny bit.

28:23.049 --> 28:24.790
Get yourself a wee sweetie.

28:24.964 --> 28:26.487
I'm not allowed, Granny.

28:26.661 --> 28:28.619
My da says you can't afford it.

28:28.794 --> 28:30.230
I'm always saying
to your man there

28:30.404 --> 28:32.232
what's yours is mine
and what's mine's me own.

28:32.406 --> 28:34.147
Thanks, Granny.

28:34.321 --> 28:37.324
Try and find out
how that wee girl thinks.

28:37.498 --> 28:38.934
Oh, good luck
with that one, son.

28:51.033 --> 28:53.470
♪ From the dark end
of the street ♪

28:56.386 --> 28:58.911
♪ To the bright side
of the road ♪

29:01.304 --> 29:04.220
♪ We'll be lovers once again ♪

29:04.394 --> 29:06.962
♪ On the bright side
of the road ♪

29:12.925 --> 29:14.578
♪ Little darlin', come with me ♪

29:14.753 --> 29:16.102
-Pass it. Pass it.
-No.

29:16.276 --> 29:17.886
Goal!

29:18.060 --> 29:19.975
♪ Won't you help me
share my load? ♪

29:20.149 --> 29:21.629
SOLDIER:
Yes, mate, over here.

29:21.803 --> 29:23.022
You just need to tell us
where you been, all right?

29:23.196 --> 29:24.675
♪ From the dark end
of the street ♪

29:24.850 --> 29:26.199
-Whoa, whoa, whoa.
-Yeah, up against the wall.

29:26.373 --> 29:28.114
♪ To the bright side
of the road ♪

29:29.724 --> 29:30.899
♪ Cricket. ♪

29:33.510 --> 29:35.164
:
Will.

29:36.905 --> 29:38.385
Will.

29:39.386 --> 29:41.518
What road do we take?

29:41.692 --> 29:43.694
I can't remember.

29:44.739 --> 29:46.088
What road did the minister say?

29:46.262 --> 29:48.264
Oh, shut up.

29:54.140 --> 29:55.750
-

29:55.924 --> 29:57.491
NEWSMAN: And in this
already tense atmosphere,

29:57.665 --> 29:59.667
concerns remain about
intimidation run rife

29:59.841 --> 30:01.451
in working-class areas.

30:01.625 --> 30:03.192
Further reports suggest...

30:03.366 --> 30:04.715
-BILLY: ...arse up here.
Come on. -BILLY JUNIOR: Daddy!

30:04.890 --> 30:06.108
Stop dragging your arse
along there. Come on.

30:06.282 --> 30:07.501
BILLY JUNIOR:
You're hurting my arm.

30:07.675 --> 30:08.937
BILLY: Right, stop being
a crybaby now.

30:09.111 --> 30:10.243
You show me where he lives.
Come on.

30:10.417 --> 30:11.635
BILLY JUNIOR:
Daddy, I'm sorry.

30:11.810 --> 30:13.550
Can you tell me
exactly what he said?

30:13.724 --> 30:15.161
He just said he couldn't give
any more money to the streets.

30:15.335 --> 30:16.858
-He'll not say that to my son.
-Daddy, stop!

30:17.032 --> 30:18.947
-Stewart! Stewart!
-Please!

30:19.121 --> 30:20.688
FRANKIE: Hey, your blood's
up there, Billy.

30:20.862 --> 30:22.559
Would you go back to your house?

30:22.733 --> 30:23.952
MR. STEWART: Right, Billy,
we've no call for fists here.

30:24.126 --> 30:25.649
Aye?
Well, what is it the man says?

30:25.824 --> 30:28.870
A fist is only as good or bad
as the man using it.

30:29.044 --> 30:30.263
Remember that.

30:34.397 --> 30:35.529
FRANKIE:
Holy God. Billy!

30:35.703 --> 30:37.139
Shut up, Frankie!

30:37.313 --> 30:38.967
WOMAN: Come on, Billy.
That's too much now.

30:39.141 --> 30:40.839
-Come on, you! -MAN: We don't
need more of this, Billy.

30:41.013 --> 30:42.405
WOMAN 2: Ah, Billy, stop that.
You're settling old scores.

30:42.579 --> 30:43.842
Regards to your pa.

30:44.016 --> 30:46.540
Tell him I expect to hear
from him soon.

30:46.714 --> 30:48.020
Or he'll be hearing from me.

30:48.194 --> 30:49.935
Up them stairs.

30:55.331 --> 30:56.419
-

30:59.727 --> 31:02.904
-♪ You don't
have to buy me flowers ♪

31:03.078 --> 31:05.385
♪ Or pretty ribbons
for my hair... ♪

31:05.559 --> 31:07.343
What are you doing?

31:07.517 --> 31:11.173
It's, like,
what my favorite holiday is.

