39:38.376 --> 39:41.509
♪ Simply love her ♪

39:41.683 --> 39:42.945
GRANNY:
Get off me.

39:43.119 --> 39:46.035
POP:
♪ Merely love her. ♪

39:55.480 --> 39:57.656
-MISS LEWIS: Walk, please.

39:57.830 --> 39:59.614
No running, thank you.

39:59.788 --> 40:01.094
Thanks.

40:02.138 --> 40:03.792
Well done on your maths.

40:03.966 --> 40:05.620
Thanks.

40:05.794 --> 40:07.796
Have you gone to the moon yet?

40:08.797 --> 40:10.799
Do you want to, with me?

40:12.410 --> 40:15.108
It'll save you getting cold
waiting outside our house.

40:19.329 --> 40:20.809
MOIRA:
Hey, Romeo, come on!

40:20.983 --> 40:23.072
We have work to do.

40:23.246 --> 40:25.205
Operation Steal The Chocolate.

40:25.379 --> 40:27.120
It's simple.
We go into the shop

40:27.294 --> 40:28.904
and keep Mr. Singh talking
down by the fridge.

40:29.078 --> 40:30.819
He has to move the boxes
round at the bottom

40:30.993 --> 40:32.299
to get me a Lemon Mivvi.

40:32.473 --> 40:34.170
His head'll be down
part of the time.

40:34.344 --> 40:36.129
You stay at the front
of the shop,

40:36.303 --> 40:39.437
and when you see he's not
looking, you make a sweep.

40:39.611 --> 40:41.830
-What's a sweep? -A big grab
for all the chocolate bars

40:42.004 --> 40:43.702
on that low shelf
near the till.

40:43.876 --> 40:45.878
Sure he'll know they've been
nicked if there's a big gap.

40:46.052 --> 40:47.793
I thought you said
we'd just do a couple,

40:47.967 --> 40:49.490
so he'd never even notice.

40:49.664 --> 40:51.013
I don't want lifted
by the police.

40:51.187 --> 40:52.275
All right, all right.

40:52.450 --> 40:53.668
-GIRL: All clear.
-No sweep.

40:53.842 --> 40:55.322
Just a small grab, okay?

40:55.496 --> 40:57.106
I might be able to swipe you
a chocolate mousse

40:57.280 --> 40:58.804
-at the same time.
-Okay.

41:03.461 --> 41:05.114
-MOIRA: Hello, Mr. Singh.
-Hello, Moira. Hello, Buddy.

41:05.288 --> 41:06.638
-BUDDY: Hello, Mr. Singh.
-MR. SINGH: Good to see youse.

41:06.812 --> 41:08.117
MOIRA: Please may I have
a Lemon Mivvi?

41:08.291 --> 41:09.554
MR. SINGH:
Lemon Mivvi coming right up.

41:09.728 --> 41:11.643
Just need to move
a few wee boxes.

41:11.817 --> 41:13.209
-Hey!
-

41:13.383 --> 41:14.776
-He's seen us!
-Come here, you wee buggers!

41:14.950 --> 41:17.039
-I know who you are!
-MOIRA: No, he doesn't!

41:17.213 --> 41:20.260
BUDDY: Well, your woman
will tell him anyway!

41:20.434 --> 41:21.696
-You proud of yourself?
-It was Moira.

41:21.870 --> 41:23.481
Get in there.

41:23.655 --> 41:25.308
MAN: Get off that blinking road
or you'll kill somebody!

41:25.483 --> 41:27.093
She's gonna tell on us!

41:27.267 --> 41:29.269
She says anything,
she's done for!

41:29.443 --> 41:30.792
WOMAN:
I know who youse are!

41:36.319 --> 41:38.365
What have you got?

41:38.539 --> 41:41.020
You're joking me.

41:41.194 --> 41:42.500
It's all I could see.

41:42.674 --> 41:44.066
Turkish Delight?

41:44.240 --> 41:45.981
Who the hell
eats Turkish Delight?

41:46.155 --> 41:48.201
-Do you eat Turkish Delight?
-No.

41:48.375 --> 41:49.550
I don't like it.

41:49.724 --> 41:52.379
Nobody likes it.

41:52.553 --> 41:54.555
-It's all they had.
-Are you blind?

41:54.729 --> 41:56.035
I had to think quickly.

41:56.209 --> 41:57.558
Not quickly enough.

41:57.732 --> 42:00.343
There was Flakes and Crunchies.

42:00.518 --> 42:02.824
All you need is an in and out
with a fast hand,

42:02.998 --> 42:05.131
and then the Milky Bars
are on me.

42:05.305 --> 42:06.915
I'm not sure
you're cut out for this.

42:07.089 --> 42:09.570
-Hey, Buddy, your da's home.

42:09.744 --> 42:12.530
-Sure it's only Wednesday.
-He came in a taxi.

42:13.705 --> 42:15.576
-And you, too!
-What?

42:15.750 --> 42:17.752
Keep your mouth shut.

42:23.192 --> 42:25.020
PA:
When did you write to them?

42:25.194 --> 42:26.674
MA:
None of your business.

42:26.848 --> 42:28.241
PA: Just tell me.
When did you write to them?

42:28.415 --> 42:29.634
-It's a simple question.
-None of your business.

42:29.808 --> 42:31.505
PA:
Just give me a simple answer.

42:31.679 --> 42:33.681
-I'm not getting interrogated.
-When did you write to them?

42:33.855 --> 42:35.509
MA: When the last receipt
came through.

42:35.683 --> 42:37.250
I knew it was the last one
'cause for three bloody years

42:37.424 --> 42:38.817
I've been counting
them envelopes

42:38.991 --> 42:40.209
coming through that door,
and there wasn't

42:40.383 --> 42:41.602
so much as a thank-you
with this one.

42:41.776 --> 42:43.299
PA: It's the taxman,
for God's sake.

42:43.473 --> 42:44.736
Who do you expect,
Father Christmas?

42:44.910 --> 42:46.564
MA: We've been
scrimping and saving,

42:46.738 --> 42:49.001
and they hadn't the good grace
as to say, "That's it.

42:49.175 --> 42:50.524
You're done.
You're in the clear."

42:50.698 --> 42:52.526
So what'd you say to them
in your letter?

42:52.700 --> 42:55.485
I said I wanted
a full official declaration

42:55.660 --> 42:57.836
that my husband was
in the clear a hundred percent

42:58.010 --> 43:00.534
on all back taxes,
and that they acknowledged

43:00.708 --> 43:03.145
that everything was shipshape
and above board,

43:03.319 --> 43:04.494
and that my family's good name

43:04.669 --> 43:06.540
wasn't on
some credit risk list.

43:06.714 --> 43:09.151
-Christ. Christ the night.
-What?

43:13.242 --> 43:14.635
No.

43:14.809 --> 43:16.768
-No.
-Yes, yes, oh, yes.

43:16.942 --> 43:19.118
They've decided-- thanks
to acting on your request--

43:19.292 --> 43:21.773
they've decided to go back
further into my accounts

43:21.947 --> 43:24.036
and say that I owe
another 572 pound,

43:24.210 --> 43:25.646
which based on
current earnings,

43:25.820 --> 43:27.474
should take another
five years to pay off.

43:27.648 --> 43:29.389
So it's a handy wee letter
you sent, wasn't it?

43:29.563 --> 43:30.999
You bugger!

43:31.173 --> 43:32.958
-Oh, you're a lying bugger!
-

43:33.132 --> 43:35.351
Aye, that's right, believe the
taxman before you believe me!

43:39.704 --> 43:41.270
Your work won't be too pleased

43:41.444 --> 43:43.882
with you skipping off
in the week.

43:44.056 --> 43:45.274
I'll work the weekend.

43:45.448 --> 43:47.320
Ah, when's that job finish?

43:47.494 --> 43:49.017
This one's nearly done.

43:49.191 --> 43:51.585
What, there's another one
over there, is there?

43:51.759 --> 43:53.282
Aye. Big one.

43:53.456 --> 43:55.154
A long one.

43:55.328 --> 43:57.243
They're asking some of the boys
to move over permanent.

43:57.417 --> 43:59.680
Offering accommodation
because of the time involved.

43:59.854 --> 44:01.160
Couple of years.

44:01.334 --> 44:03.118
Building a hospital.

44:03.292 --> 44:05.251
Your father has to go
to the hospital.

44:05.425 --> 44:06.687
You talk to him about it.

44:06.861 --> 44:08.515
Won't talk to me about doctors.

44:08.689 --> 44:09.734
Is that right?

44:09.908 --> 44:11.736
Ah, it's just a couple of days.

44:11.910 --> 44:14.042
A wee test for the lungs.

44:14.216 --> 44:16.218
It's all that bloody time
over in Leicester.

44:16.392 --> 44:18.438
-Where's that?
-In England.

44:18.612 --> 44:20.266
Is that near where Daddy works?

44:20.440 --> 44:22.703
Nah, your daddy works near,
uh, London, the Big Smoke.

44:22.877 --> 44:25.053
This was in the countryside.

44:25.227 --> 44:26.533
What were you doing?

44:26.707 --> 44:28.143
I was a coal miner.

44:28.317 --> 44:29.928
You've done a lot
of different jobs, Pop.

44:30.102 --> 44:31.538
You can say that again.

44:31.712 --> 44:34.062
Yeah, none of them lasted
more than a week.

44:35.455 --> 44:37.413
My mother's worried about you.

44:37.587 --> 44:39.502
Your mother's worried about you.

44:41.069 --> 44:44.029
Well, Granny's always worried
about something, isn't she?

44:44.203 --> 44:46.901
Ah, well, your granny's
a very caring person.

44:47.075 --> 44:49.077
Sometimes it affects her nerves.

44:49.251 --> 44:50.426
Like your mommy.

44:50.600 --> 44:53.168
Mommy's worried, too, isn't she?

44:56.432 --> 44:59.914
Daddy, are we gonna
have to leave Belfast?

45:02.569 --> 45:05.006
PA: All right, Buddy,
that's me away, then.

45:05.180 --> 45:06.660
I'll see you
when I get back next week.

45:06.834 --> 45:08.444
MISS LEWIS: In you come, girls.
Catherine. Quinn.

45:08.618 --> 45:10.229
Come on in, girls. You can help
put the pencils out.

45:10.403 --> 45:12.100
PA:
Be good, son.

45:12.274 --> 45:13.493
If you can't be good?

45:13.667 --> 45:15.669
BOTH:
Be careful.

45:16.801 --> 45:18.411
BILLY:
Seems like only yesterday

45:18.585 --> 45:21.022
you and me were
in school together.

45:21.196 --> 45:23.982
You're gonna need to stay
away from my family.

45:24.156 --> 45:26.245
BILLY: That's big talk
for a fella who's never here.

45:26.419 --> 45:28.595
PA: You can rely on me
to be here when it matters.

45:28.769 --> 45:30.336
BILLY:
I hope your timing's good.

45:30.510 --> 45:33.165
Things get out of hand
pretty quick round these parts.

45:35.341 --> 45:38.300
Do you know the problem
with men like you?

45:38.474 --> 45:40.650
You think you're better
than the rest of us.

45:40.825 --> 45:43.915
And the problem with men like
you is you know you're not.

45:46.482 --> 45:48.093
We'll keep it simple.

45:49.572 --> 45:51.749
You're with us
or you're against us.

45:51.923 --> 45:52.924
Clock's ticking.

45:53.098 --> 45:54.403
You're a soft touch!

45:54.577 --> 45:56.405
Time for real Protestants
to step up!

45:56.579 --> 45:58.059
PA:
Ach, you're no real Protestant.

45:58.233 --> 46:00.801
You're a jumped-up gangster
and always were.

46:17.949 --> 46:19.646
MAN: There's peelers about.
Hey, watch it, youse two.

46:19.820 --> 46:21.300
WOMAN:
Quick.

46:29.569 --> 46:32.137
MA: Ah, look.
There you are now, son.

46:37.620 --> 46:39.318
Hello, son.

46:39.492 --> 46:41.624
The police officer here
just wants a wee word with you.

46:41.799 --> 46:43.452
There seems to be
a-a wee bit of confusion

46:43.626 --> 46:45.672
about something that happened
at Mr. Singh's.

46:45.846 --> 46:47.892
Go on, sit down there, now.

46:53.288 --> 46:55.856
POLICEMAN:
Do you know why I'm here, son?

46:56.030 --> 46:58.424
Don't lie to me.

46:58.598 --> 47:00.252
A very serious crime
has been committed

47:00.426 --> 47:01.819
down in Mr. Singh's shop.

47:01.993 --> 47:04.082
Do you know
what I'm talking about?

47:07.476 --> 47:09.827
All the best, now,
and give my regards to Josie.

47:10.001 --> 47:12.220
-POLICEMAN: I will do.
-I do like a man in a uniform.

47:12.394 --> 47:14.875
Was he in there long?

47:15.049 --> 47:17.530
Apples'll grow again, should
they grow on a gooseberry tree!

47:17.704 --> 47:19.532
I didn't even
eat the chocolate!

47:19.706 --> 47:22.840
: No, I won't
be here when it's over.

47:23.014 --> 47:24.711
You're asking me
to wait an hour to find out

47:24.885 --> 47:26.713
if I'm going to be
a wife or a widow.

47:26.887 --> 47:28.410
I say it's too long to wait.

47:28.584 --> 47:30.108
-I won't do it.
-WILL KANE: Amy...

47:30.282 --> 47:32.458
I mean it.
If you won't go with me now,

47:32.632 --> 47:34.939
I'll be on that train
when it leaves here.

47:36.157 --> 47:37.811
I've got to stay.

47:37.985 --> 47:39.857
No, you're not listening to me.

47:40.031 --> 47:42.033
:
I am listening. I am listening.

47:42.207 --> 47:43.556
Would you, would you listen
to me for a change?

47:43.730 --> 47:45.514
I'm trying to be practical
about this.

47:45.688 --> 47:47.299
MA: Look, the police were here
today but their father wasn't,

47:47.473 --> 47:48.822
so, no, I'll not be
having any lectures

47:48.996 --> 47:50.215
-from you, mister.
-Don't be like that.

47:50.389 --> 47:51.999
I know what you're gonna...

47:58.832 --> 48:02.140
♪ Do not forsake me,
oh, my darling ♪

48:03.793 --> 48:08.537
♪ On this our wedding day ♪

48:08.711 --> 48:14.717
♪ Do not forsake me,
oh, my darling ♪

48:14.892 --> 48:17.503
♪ Wait ♪

48:17.677 --> 48:20.898
♪ Wait along ♪

48:21.072 --> 48:26.860
♪ I do not know
what fate awaits me ♪

48:27.034 --> 48:32.866
♪ I only know I must be brave ♪

48:33.040 --> 48:36.087
♪ And I must face
a man who hates me ♪

48:36.261 --> 48:37.697
:
Clear the streets

48:37.871 --> 48:38.916
and return to your homes.

48:39.090 --> 48:41.919
♪ Or lie a coward ♪

48:42.093 --> 48:43.790
♪ A craven coward ♪

48:43.964 --> 48:45.226
Return to your homes.

48:45.400 --> 48:50.275
♪ Or lie a coward in my grave ♪

48:50.449 --> 48:51.841
Oi. Yes, I'm open.

48:52.016 --> 48:53.669
-♪ Wait along ♪
-Catch it.

48:53.843 --> 48:55.019
-Mine, mine, mine!
-Pass it to me!

48:55.193 --> 48:56.150
♪ Wait along... ♪

48:56.324 --> 48:57.935
Mrs. Ford, how you doing?

48:58.109 --> 48:59.588
MRS. FORD: All the better
for seeing you, stranger.

48:59.762 --> 49:01.416
-Welcome home. -Ah, you're
a silver-tongued charmer.

49:01.590 --> 49:03.941
-It takes one to know one.
- All right?

49:04.115 --> 49:05.420
MR. STEWART:
Ah, just the fella.

49:05.594 --> 49:07.118
Have you got a horse
for the 2:30 race?

49:07.292 --> 49:08.728
I have, but if I tell you,
the odds'll come down.

49:08.902 --> 49:11.209
Christ, I'm not gonna
bet the house.

49:11.383 --> 49:13.211
Fancy Man, each way.
She'll get you a pint.

49:13.385 --> 49:16.083
-Is that Paddy moving out?
-Poor Catholics have no choice.

49:16.257 --> 49:17.693
-It's a mad world.
-Well, get used to it.

49:17.867 --> 49:19.434
We all live there now.

49:20.479 --> 49:21.871
NEWSMAN:
Prize capture was a tanker

49:22.046 --> 49:24.744
laden with
2,500 gallons of petrol.

49:24.918 --> 49:27.138
They'd also taken dozens
of crates of milk bottles

49:27.312 --> 49:29.575
from a passing truck and
dubbed the whole enterprise

49:29.749 --> 49:31.316
the Petrol Bomb Factory.

49:31.490 --> 49:33.448
MA: Sure all the kids in
the street are going mad.

49:33.622 --> 49:35.146
PA:
What do you want me to do?

49:35.320 --> 49:37.539
MA:
You need to talk to them boys.

49:43.850 --> 49:45.634
How many was there?

49:45.808 --> 49:47.854
About ten of them.

49:48.028 --> 49:50.465
And what did your mate do?

49:50.639 --> 49:54.121
He said he wasn't joining
anything they belonged to.

49:54.295 --> 49:57.429
Then he gave the big one a dig
in the gob and ran like hell.

49:57.603 --> 49:59.344
So did I.

49:59.518 --> 50:01.346
Did they chase you?

50:01.520 --> 50:03.435
Aye, but we got
a street ahead of them.

50:03.609 --> 50:05.741
Then we ran into me Uncle
Tony's and turned the corner

50:05.915 --> 50:07.700
before they could see us.

50:07.874 --> 50:09.876
We put the heart across
me Uncle Tony.

50:10.050 --> 50:11.921
He was on the toilet,
doing his horses,

50:12.096 --> 50:14.576
and then he dropped his pencil
down the loo.

50:15.882 --> 50:18.276
You've delivered
for these boys before, aye?

50:18.450 --> 50:20.278
Mm-hmm.

50:20.452 --> 50:22.106
And you know it's not milk
they're putting

50:22.280 --> 50:24.543
back in them empty bottles?

50:24.717 --> 50:26.371
I do now, Daddy.

50:28.590 --> 50:30.636
You were right to tell me.

50:33.421 --> 50:35.380
Come here and hold this, son.

50:36.685 --> 50:38.078
Hold that there.

50:42.474 --> 50:44.432
-You got that?
-Mm-hmm.

50:44.606 --> 50:47.435
REPORTER: And amid more
citywide violence overnight,

50:47.609 --> 50:49.916
government figures issued today
reveal that Northern Ireland

50:50.090 --> 50:52.962
now has the highest rate
of unemployment in the UK.

50:53.137 --> 50:55.095
PA:
Here it is. Planet Earth.

50:55.269 --> 50:56.792
And do you know where that is?

50:56.966 --> 50:58.707
-Sydney.
-Australia?

50:58.881 --> 51:00.361
Aye, that's right.

51:00.535 --> 51:02.059
-Do you know about it?
-Aye.

51:02.233 --> 51:03.930
They've got surfing
and weird football.

51:04.104 --> 51:05.671
And they have kangaroos
on the barbecue.

51:05.845 --> 51:07.151
And the weather's good.

51:07.325 --> 51:08.848
Young Joe Turner's
down there, too.

51:09.022 --> 51:10.284
That's right.

51:10.458 --> 51:12.156
How do you fancy that?

51:12.330 --> 51:13.548
What?

51:13.722 --> 51:15.550
Moving over there
for a wee while.

51:15.724 --> 51:17.074
You're joking.

51:17.248 --> 51:18.901
No. It's just down the side
a wee bit.

51:19.076 --> 51:20.468
It's ten and a half
thousand miles.

51:20.642 --> 51:22.905
Right, school, you two-- now.

51:27.649 --> 51:30.304
We might as well be going to
the moon if we went down there.

51:30.478 --> 51:31.871
Sure, you've already
family there.

51:32.045 --> 51:33.133
One second cousin.

51:33.307 --> 51:34.569
And you've the phone.

51:34.743 --> 51:37.355
And a millionaire
to pay the bills?

51:37.529 --> 51:39.052
We could take trips back.

51:39.226 --> 51:41.228
And pay for it with what,
Scotch mist?

51:41.402 --> 51:43.361
Family could come over
for holidays.

51:43.535 --> 51:45.058
I didn't come up the loch
in a bubble.

51:45.232 --> 51:46.538
There's no one from round here

51:46.712 --> 51:48.148
can afford the fare
to go down there.

51:48.322 --> 51:50.368
Or the time off work,
if they had any work.

51:50.542 --> 51:51.978
You just heard the bloody news.

51:52.152 --> 51:53.762
We have to do something.

51:53.936 --> 51:55.895
This is our home.

51:58.245 --> 52:00.073
-

52:08.690 --> 52:11.345
♪ When it's not
always raining ♪

52:11.519 --> 52:13.913
♪ There'll be days like this ♪

52:14.087 --> 52:16.524
♪ When there's no one
complaining ♪

52:16.698 --> 52:18.918
-♪ There'll be days like this ♪
-

52:19.092 --> 52:20.920
♪ Everything falls into place ♪

52:21.094 --> 52:22.791
♪ Like the flick of a switch ♪

52:24.663 --> 52:26.708
-♪ Well, my mama told me ♪
-

52:26.882 --> 52:29.363
♪ There'll be days like this ♪

52:31.365 --> 52:32.932
I hope you're feeling
confident, Daddy.

52:33.106 --> 52:34.716
♪ When you don't need to worry ♪

52:34.890 --> 52:36.370
♪ There'll be days like this ♪

52:36.544 --> 52:38.067
Don't worry.

52:38.242 --> 52:39.808
♪ When on one's in a hurry ♪

52:39.982 --> 52:42.594
-♪ There'll be days like this ♪
-

52:42.768 --> 52:44.422
♪ When you don't get
betrayed... ♪

52:44.596 --> 52:46.859
VIOLET:
He's away the night again?

52:47.033 --> 52:49.383
MA:
Aye, he can't neglect his work.

52:49.557 --> 52:51.124
VIOLET:
Sure, there's work here.

52:51.298 --> 52:53.474
MA:
Have you read the papers?

52:53.648 --> 52:55.389
You'd break my heart
to leave, but...

52:55.563 --> 52:57.086
-BOY: Come on!
-GIRL: Here!

52:57.261 --> 53:00.002
...you have to think of them.

53:00.177 --> 53:02.048
We can't all leave.

53:02.222 --> 53:03.919
There'd be nobody left
but the nutters.

53:04.093 --> 53:06.618
: Aye, and nobody
to cook their tea,

53:06.792 --> 53:09.273
run messages
and wipe their arses.

53:09.447 --> 53:12.493
That'd make the violence stop
in about ten minutes.

53:12.667 --> 53:15.583
-

53:15.757 --> 53:18.151
How could I leave Belfast?

53:18.325 --> 53:20.066
I wouldn't worry about it.

53:20.240 --> 53:22.460
The Irish were born for leaving.

53:22.634 --> 53:25.202
Otherwise, the rest of
the world would have no pubs.

53:27.116 --> 53:28.944
It just needs half of us to stay

53:29.118 --> 53:30.903
so that the other half
can get sentimental

53:31.077 --> 53:33.471
-about the ones that went.
-

53:33.645 --> 53:36.561
All the Irish need to survive
is a phone, a Guinness

53:36.735 --> 53:39.651
and the sheet music
to "Danny Boy."

53:39.825 --> 53:42.001
You're a terrible woman,
you know that?

53:42.175 --> 53:44.699
-PA: He shoots, he scores.

53:47.615 --> 53:51.445
♪ The summer's gone ♪

53:51.619 --> 53:55.144
♪ And all the flowers ♪

53:55.319 --> 53:56.537
♪ Are dying ♪

53:56.711 --> 53:58.017
PA:
I'll see you soon, okay?

53:58.191 --> 54:00.672
♪ 'Tis you, 'tis you ♪

54:00.846 --> 54:02.761
-MA: You take her home.
-♪ Must go ♪

54:02.935 --> 54:04.763
-PA: Enjoy yourself, okay?
-♪ And I must bide ♪

54:04.937 --> 54:06.547
Come on, now, missus.
Come along.

54:06.721 --> 54:08.593
We must go as well.
Come on, now.

54:08.767 --> 54:12.249
♪ But come ye back... ♪

54:12.423 --> 54:14.251
All right, I give in.

54:14.425 --> 54:16.253
-

54:16.427 --> 54:21.388
♪ When summer's in the... ♪

54:21.562 --> 54:24.609
-Violet, can I ask you
a question? -What?

54:24.783 --> 54:27.742
-What did you do
with the money? -What money?

54:27.916 --> 54:30.092
MACK: The money your ma
gave you for singing lessons.

54:32.269 --> 54:34.706
: All passengers
departing on the Heysham ferry

54:34.880 --> 54:37.796
should proceed
to the boarding area now.

54:37.970 --> 54:40.189
Everybody's leaving home.

54:40.364 --> 54:42.366
People have to move on.

54:44.890 --> 54:49.373
"Too long a sacrifice can make
a stone of the heart."

54:49.547 --> 54:51.288
Oh, is that what does it?

54:51.462 --> 54:53.333
Yeah, well, you don't usually
buy your wisdom

54:53.507 --> 54:55.030
with a walk in the park.

54:55.204 --> 54:57.511
Your heart has to explode.

54:57.685 --> 54:59.557
:
Mr. Philosopher.

54:59.731 --> 55:02.951
And when did your heart
ever explode?

55:03.125 --> 55:06.085
That time I saw you
in those brown stockings.

55:06.259 --> 55:09.436
:
Holy God.

55:09.610 --> 55:11.569
-Aye.
-I remember that.

55:13.701 --> 55:15.312
It took me half the day

55:15.486 --> 55:17.749
just staining my legs brown
with the tobacco water.

55:17.923 --> 55:20.012
Then our Annie took
half the night

55:20.186 --> 55:22.884
to draw the seam up the back
of my legs with a pencil.

55:23.058 --> 55:24.495
You couldn't understand why

55:24.669 --> 55:26.148
you couldn't get your hands
round them.

55:26.323 --> 55:29.108
-You thought it was magic.

55:29.282 --> 55:32.024
It was magic.

55:32.198 --> 55:36.333
When you've gray hair, people
think your heart never skipped.

55:36.507 --> 55:38.073
Did yours ever skip?

55:38.247 --> 55:39.640
Aye, it danced a bloody jig

55:39.814 --> 55:41.338
every time you walked
in the room.

55:41.512 --> 55:43.035
-Nah.
-

55:43.209 --> 55:45.254
You were full of it then,
and you're full of it now.

55:45.429 --> 55:47.169
Come on. We may get on.

55:48.562 --> 55:50.912
Uh, Jimmy said he'd drive me

55:51.086 --> 55:52.566
to the hospital in the morning.

55:52.740 --> 55:54.699
No, and I told him he would not.

55:56.265 --> 55:58.616
I'm taking you in on the bus.

55:58.790 --> 56:01.096
I'm walking you in,
and when they're done,

56:01.270 --> 56:04.143
you can be bloody sure
I'm walking you back out again.

56:05.318 --> 56:06.972
Do you hear me?

56:07.146 --> 56:08.669
I'm walking you home.

56:08.843 --> 56:10.105
Do you hear me?

56:10.279 --> 56:12.586
Yeah, I hear you, missus.

56:14.545 --> 56:16.634
Sure, when did I not?

56:32.998 --> 56:33.825
DRIVER: Aldergrove bus going
in three minutes.

56:33.999 --> 56:35.174
Last tickets now.

56:35.348 --> 56:36.741
PA:
The boss has been in touch.

56:36.915 --> 56:38.612
They want me to stay on.

56:38.786 --> 56:41.006
A permanent job in England.

56:41.180 --> 56:43.574
Wanting me to move
into management.

56:43.748 --> 56:45.140
It's more money.

56:45.314 --> 56:46.533
MAN:
Just let us through there.

56:46.707 --> 56:48.100
There's a house
that goes with it.

56:48.274 --> 56:49.710
We get it rent-free,

56:49.884 --> 56:52.365
with a chance to own it
if things go well.

56:52.539 --> 56:54.280
A wee bit bigger
than what we have here.

56:54.454 --> 56:55.934
A room for each of the boys.

56:56.108 --> 56:57.718
There's a wee garden, too.

56:57.892 --> 57:00.025
Are you allowed to play
football in that garden, Daddy?

57:00.199 --> 57:01.766
PA:
Aye, son.

57:01.940 --> 57:04.203
If I say yes, there's
more money straightaway.

57:04.377 --> 57:06.597
We could start getting on top
of that back tax now.

57:07.815 --> 57:09.295
This family's not gonna get
another chance like that

57:09.469 --> 57:10.731
in this town, not now.

57:13.038 --> 57:14.692
Hey, watch out
for that traffic there.

57:14.866 --> 57:17.608
I'm watching it now, Mammy.
It's okay.

57:17.782 --> 57:19.871
DRIVER:
Come on, now. Two minutes.

57:20.045 --> 57:22.743
Get on board if you're coming.
Last tickets now.

57:27.400 --> 57:29.663
Sounds like
they really want you.

57:34.189 --> 57:36.191
What do you want?

57:38.063 --> 57:40.065
I want my family with me.

57:41.980 --> 57:43.851
I want you.

57:47.681 --> 57:50.118
You and me,

57:50.292 --> 57:52.991
we've known each other
since we were toddlers.

57:54.253 --> 57:56.298
We've known this street

57:56.473 --> 57:59.040
and every street round it
all our lives.

58:00.346 --> 58:02.000
And every man,
woman and child that lives

58:02.174 --> 58:05.003
in every bloody house,
whether we like it or not.

58:06.613 --> 58:08.485
I like it.

58:10.182 --> 58:12.967
And you say you've
a wee garden for them boys?

58:15.100 --> 58:19.757
But here, they can play
wherever the hell they like,

58:19.931 --> 58:21.802
'cause everybody knows them,

58:21.976 --> 58:25.327
everybody likes them
and everybody looks after them.

58:26.720 --> 58:29.418
If we go over the water,

58:29.593 --> 58:32.900
them people's not gonna
understand a word we say.

58:34.336 --> 58:37.035
And half of them,
they'll take the hand out of us

58:37.209 --> 58:39.646
for sounding different.

58:39.820 --> 58:43.607
And the other half,
they'll hate us

58:43.781 --> 58:46.740
'cause men here are killing
their young sons on our streets.

58:46.914 --> 58:49.743
They'll think
we don't give a shite.

58:49.917 --> 58:52.398
And you think they're gonna
welcome us with open arms?

58:52.572 --> 58:55.444
What, and say, "Come on in.

58:55.619 --> 58:58.317
Well done for stealing
the house off of us"?

58:59.666 --> 59:01.668
Things change.

59:04.410 --> 59:06.891
Aye. They do.

59:10.503 --> 59:12.549
We need to decide by Christmas.

59:14.289 --> 59:16.553
You need to decide by Christmas.

59:18.250 --> 59:21.906
You're coming back,
aren't you, Daddy?

59:23.560 --> 59:25.953
You look after your mummy.

59:26.127 --> 59:28.347
Be good. If you can't be good...

59:28.521 --> 59:31.655
"And if you can't be good,
be careful."

59:32.656 --> 59:33.918
DRIVER:
Right, off we go.

59:34.092 --> 59:36.790
Aldergrove Airport,
ladies and gents.

59:51.457 --> 59:53.328
PA:
We'll talk on the phone, okay?

59:55.113 --> 59:56.897
MA:
Give me a ring.

59:57.071 --> 59:59.117
Tell me when you've got there.

1:00:10.650 --> 1:00:12.913
♪ I'm stranded ♪

1:00:16.047 --> 1:00:20.921
♪ At the edge of the world ♪

1:00:24.533 --> 1:00:28.450
♪ It's a world I don't know ♪

1:00:29.495 --> 1:00:32.411
♪ Got nowhere to go ♪

1:00:34.543 --> 1:00:37.459
♪ Feels like I'm stranded ♪

1:00:44.815 --> 1:00:47.121
NURSE: I caught you looking
at Dr. Kildare.

1:00:47.295 --> 1:00:50.124
-NURSE 2: Right. You can talk.

1:00:50.298 --> 1:00:52.083
POP:
Have you wrote to Santa?

1:00:52.257 --> 1:00:53.780
MA: Oh, he has,
but Santa's explained

1:00:53.954 --> 1:00:55.434
that money's
a bit tight this year,

1:00:55.608 --> 1:00:57.349
so he's not to expect too much.

1:00:57.523 --> 1:00:59.264
Sure, Santa has plenty
of surplus

1:00:59.438 --> 1:01:01.483
if you talk to
the people in the know.

1:01:01.658 --> 1:01:03.572
Your health is all you need

1:01:03.747 --> 1:01:05.792
-for a Christmas present.
-Ah. Well, you've the right one

1:01:05.966 --> 1:01:07.620
to keep you cheerful here,
haven't you, Pop?

1:01:07.794 --> 1:01:09.753
You tell your mammy
to stop her cheek,

1:01:09.927 --> 1:01:11.406
or I'm not taking you
to the show.

1:01:11.580 --> 1:01:12.843
What show's that?

1:01:13.017 --> 1:01:14.105
MA:
I don't know. I think there's

1:01:14.279 --> 1:01:15.628
Christmas carols in it, though.

1:01:15.802 --> 1:01:17.282
GRANNY: Oh, that's
me waterworks.

1:01:17.456 --> 1:01:19.023
MA:
And you, behave yourself.

1:01:19.197 --> 1:01:20.589
Don't be annoying your pop.

1:01:20.764 --> 1:01:22.113
Don't be asking
for any Christmas presents.

1:01:22.287 --> 1:01:23.375
He's no money, either.

1:01:23.549 --> 1:01:26.247
Taxman's got it, like ours.

1:01:26.421 --> 1:01:28.075
Ach, don't worry.

1:01:28.249 --> 1:01:30.948
Your mammy will persuade Santa
to bring some presents.

1:01:31.122 --> 1:01:33.341
Ach. Don't think so, Pop.

1:01:33.515 --> 1:01:34.908
I always know
when there's no money.

1:01:35.082 --> 1:01:36.562
-MAN: Hello?

1:01:36.736 --> 1:01:38.390
-It's the rent man.
-BUDDY: I'll get it, Mam.

1:01:38.564 --> 1:01:40.087
Shut your mouth.

1:01:40.261 --> 1:01:42.742
Is your mum in there, wee man?

1:01:42.916 --> 1:01:44.135
Nobody's here.

1:01:44.309 --> 1:01:45.745
-

1:01:45.919 --> 1:01:48.313
Oh, that puts me in mind
of a great wee system

1:01:48.487 --> 1:01:50.881
we had in the old days
for paying the rent.

1:01:51.055 --> 1:01:53.971
The rent man would come round
and collect the money

1:01:54.145 --> 1:01:56.147
for every house
in the whole street,

1:01:56.321 --> 1:01:58.279
and once he had done

1:01:58.453 --> 1:02:01.543
and all the rent books
were marked up to date,

1:02:01.718 --> 1:02:03.807
one of the boys would
hold him up at gunpoint

1:02:03.981 --> 1:02:05.547
in the back entry

1:02:05.722 --> 1:02:07.767
and take all the money
back off him,

1:02:07.941 --> 1:02:10.291
and then he'd hand it
straight back

1:02:10.465 --> 1:02:12.380
to all the residents
in the street,

1:02:12.554 --> 1:02:14.948
with a little commission
for the service.

1:02:15.122 --> 1:02:18.647
Yeah, it was
a very effective system.

1:02:18.822 --> 1:02:21.215
And the rent man was
so good about it in the end

1:02:21.389 --> 1:02:23.783
that eventually they cut him in
for a wee bit, too,

1:02:23.957 --> 1:02:26.307
and everybody was happy.

1:02:26.481 --> 1:02:29.136
Except for the council,
I suppose.

1:02:29.310 --> 1:02:32.052
His work's giving my da a house
in England now if he wants one.

1:02:32.226 --> 1:02:34.402
It's got a garden
and everything,

1:02:34.576 --> 1:02:37.275
and two toilets, and they're
both inside the house.

1:02:37.449 --> 1:02:39.581
There's nothing wrong
with an outside toilet,

1:02:39.756 --> 1:02:41.366
except on an aeroplane.

1:02:43.368 --> 1:02:46.023
My ma says,
if we went across the water,

1:02:46.197 --> 1:02:48.329
they wouldn't understand
the way we talk.

1:02:48.503 --> 1:02:49.983
That shouldn't be
a problem, son.

1:02:50.157 --> 1:02:51.898
I've been married
to your granny for 50 years.

1:02:52.072 --> 1:02:54.988
I've never understood
a word she's said.

1:02:55.162 --> 1:02:57.425
And if they can't
understand you,

1:02:57.599 --> 1:03:00.951
then they're not listening,
and that's their problem.

1:03:01.125 --> 1:03:02.604
You know, when I was
in Leicester,

1:03:02.779 --> 1:03:04.432
they said the same thing
about me.

1:03:04.606 --> 1:03:07.871
You know, so I put on
a different bloody accent

1:03:08.045 --> 1:03:09.655
every day just to annoy them.

1:03:09.829 --> 1:03:11.483
They never knew who I was.

1:03:11.657 --> 1:03:13.093
But I did,

1:03:13.267 --> 1:03:16.618
and that's the only one
who needs to know.

1:03:18.011 --> 1:03:19.534
You know who you are, don't you?

1:03:19.708 --> 1:03:21.232
Yes, Pop.

1:03:21.406 --> 1:03:25.714
You're Buddy from Belfast 15,

1:03:25.889 --> 1:03:27.716
where everybody knows you

1:03:27.891 --> 1:03:30.371
and your pop looks out for you

1:03:30.545 --> 1:03:32.373
and your mummy looks out
for you,

1:03:32.547 --> 1:03:34.898
your daddy looks out for you,
your granny looks out for you,

1:03:35.072 --> 1:03:36.421
your brother looks out for you,

1:03:36.595 --> 1:03:39.946
and the whole family
looks out for you.

1:03:40.120 --> 1:03:44.821
And wherever you go
and whatever you become,

1:03:44.995 --> 1:03:47.562
that'll always be the truth.

1:03:47.736 --> 1:03:50.435
And that thought
will keep you safe.

1:03:50.609 --> 1:03:53.046
It'll keep you happy.

1:03:53.220 --> 1:03:54.656
Will you remember that for me?

1:03:54.831 --> 1:03:57.137
-Yes, Pop.
-Aye.

1:03:57.311 --> 1:03:59.574
Fine man you are.

1:03:59.748 --> 1:04:02.099
Now, forget about

1:04:02.273 --> 1:04:05.058
what your father
and your mother want.

1:04:05.232 --> 1:04:07.017
What do you want?

1:04:08.148 --> 1:04:10.890
I want you
and my granny to come, too.

1:04:27.776 --> 1:04:29.735
-

1:04:29.909 --> 1:04:31.780
:
Hear me.

1:04:32.738 --> 1:04:35.436
Hear me.

